4. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

4.1 Hardware Architecture

4.1.1 Modular Design

AURA employs a modular architecture for maintainability and upgradability:

Core Module:

· Quantum processor and control electronics
· Main computers (CPU/GPU) and memory
· Power distribution and management

Mobility Module:

· Legs, hips, and balance systems
· Wheeled base attachment points
· Environmental protection systems

Manipulation Module:

· Arms with 7 degrees of freedom each
· Hands with 20 degrees of freedom each
· Tool attachment interfaces

Perception Module:

· Head with sensor array and neck articulation
· Additional body-mounted sensors
· Processing for real-time perception

Application Modules:

· Medical: Sterile tools, specialized sensors
· Rescue: Protective covers, extraction tools
· Custom: Customer-specific requirements

4.1.2 Power System

· Primary: 20kWh solid-state lithium-sulfur battery
· Secondary: Wireless charging (5kW at 85% efficiency)
· Harvesting: Solar (200W), kinetic (50W), thermal (20W)
· Emergency: Betavoltaic nuclear backup (10W for 10 years)
· Runtime: 40 hours typical, 8 hours high-intensity

4.2 Software Architecture

4.2.1 Real-Time Operating System

Custom RTOS (AURA-ROS) provides:

· Deterministic scheduling with 1μs timer resolution
· Memory protection with formal verification
· Safety certification to ISO 26262 ASIL D
· Power management with predictive idle

4.2.2 Middleware

ROS 2 customization (AURA-DDS) enables:

· Zero-copy intra-process communication
· RDMA for intra-robot data transfer
· QUIC with post-quantum encryption for remote communication
· Quality of service policies for different data types

4.2.3 Application Framework

Container-based architecture allows:

· Isolation of different applications
· Secure sandboxing of third-party code
· Dynamic loading and unloading of capabilities
· Version management and rollback

4.3 Quantum Software Stack

4.3.1 Quantum Compiler

Multi-level compilation from algorithm to pulses:

1. Algorithm level: Python with quantum extensions
2. Circuit level: Abstract quantum operations
3. Device level: Native gate set and connectivity
4. Pulse level: Analog control waveforms
5. Machine code: Binary for control hardware

4.3.2 Quantum Runtime

· Just-in-time compilation with caching
· Dynamic resource allocation and scheduling
· Error mitigation and correction
· Interface to classical machine learning

4.4 Security Architecture

4.4.1 Defense in Depth

Six-layer security model:

1. Physical: Tamper detection and response
2. Boot: Verified chain of trust from ROM
3. Platform: Trusted execution environment
4. Network: Firewalls, intrusion detection, VPN
5. Application: Sandboxing and least privilege
6. Data: Encryption at rest and in transit

4.4.2 Quantum-Resistant Cryptography

· Encryption: CRYSTALS-Kyber (post-quantum KEM)
· Signatures: CRYSTALS-Dilithium (post-quantum signatures)
· Key distribution: Quantum key distribution (BB84 protocol)
· Key management: Hardware security module with quantum RNG

4.4.3 Continuous Security Monitoring

· Security information and event management (SIEM)
· Behavioral anomaly detection with machine learning
· Automated threat intelligence updates
· Incident response playbooks for common scenarios

